[2]
Bluetongue in Spain
-------------------
Follow-up report No. 5
See also: reports between 10 Dec 2004 and 31 Oct 2003
Translation of information received on 9 Dec 2004 (and until) from Dr
Arnaldo Cabello Navarro, deputy director general of animal health, Ministry
of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, Madrid:
End of previous report period: 25 Nov 2004 (see Disease Information 2004;
17[49]: 360, 3 Dec, and 17[50]: 373, 10 Dec).
New outbreaks:
Location: Extremadura Autonomous Community, Badajoz province, Badajoz
municipality
No. of outbreaks: 2
Extremadura Autonomous Community, Badajoz province, Cheles municipality
No. of outbreaks: 1
Extremadura Autonomous Community, Badajoz province, Don Benito (Las Monjas)
municipality
No. of outbreaks: 8
Total: 11
Description of affected population in the new outbreaks: cattle and sheep.
Total number of animals in the new outbreaks:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
ovi / 9167 / 233 / 15 / 14 / 0
bov / 1433 / 0 / 0 / 0 / 0
The diagnosis of bluetongue virus serotype 4 was made at the Central
Veterinary Laboratory, Algete, using enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay
(ELISA) and polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
B. Mode of spread: unknown.
Control measures:
- control of arthropods;
- modified stamping out;
- processing of dead animals in authorised plants in accordance with the
standards in force;
- movement control inside the country;
- zoning.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Geographically, the outbreaks -- involving thousands of cases and hundreds
of deaths -- continue in the south western part of Spain. The newest
outbreaks are close to the Portuguese border in Badajoz province. - Mod.PC]
